# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Phoenix was the Rim Worlds Republic's first jump-capable BattleMech, designed and manufactured by Krauss-Liemann Incorporated on Wotan. Following the success of the Terran Hegemony's Wasp, First Consul Terens Amaris became convinced that jump jet technology represented a fundamental shift in BattleMech tactics and ordered the development of a heavier jump-capable design. Originally conceived in the late 2460s, the project stalled when Republic engineers were forced to reverse-engineer jump jet technology acquired through intelligence operations. Amaris' insistence on "quality over quantity" diverted resources from other programs, delaying the Phoenix's introduction until 2520, well after the Hegemony had fielded the Griffin and Shadow Hawk.</p><p>Produced exclusively for the Republic's military, the fifty-ton Phoenix filled a unique role as a medium-weight trooper capable of executing combat drops from DropShips and engaging enemies at multiple ranges. A secondary production line was also established at Diplass BattleMechs on Apollo, expanding the Republic's manufacturing base for this design.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Phoenix is built around a Magna 250 fusion engine that propels the fifty-ton 'Mech to a top speed of 86 kilometers per hour. Five Gerard Special A jump jets grant a maximum jump distance of 150 meters, providing tactical flexibility that most medium 'Mechs of its era could not match. Nine tons of PanzerSlab Type 3 standard armor provide reasonable protection for its weight class, though the design clearly prioritizes mobility over survivability.</p><p>The primary armament centers on a Stolz Harbinger 2 particle projector cannon, making the Phoenix an effective sniper at long range. Two Marklin Mini SRM-2 launchers supplement the PPC at closer ranges, with dual ammunition bins allowing MechWarriors to carry different munition types including inferno missiles. This combination gave Phoenix formations considerable tactical versatility, particularly when rotating damaged 'Mechs through firing positions to distribute armor damage across the unit.</p><p>The 12b Krauss-Liemann chassis proved adequate for its era, though the Phoenix suffered from persistent electromagnetic interference whenever its particle cannon fired, a flaw serious enough to earn it the nickname "Sparkly Bird" among pilots. The Vex/Holden TriComm Plus communications system and Dillon QuadTrac targeting system with integrated Particle Cannon Suite helped compensate for these issues but never fully eliminated them.</p>

deployment:<p>This variant represents the fully modernized production model of the Phoenix, introduced in 2520 after decades of development work corrected the problems that plagued the primitive prototype. Mounting a Stolz Harbinger 2 PPC as its primary weapon with twin Marklin Mini SRM-2 launchers for close support, the 3R was the definitive version of the design that served the Rim Worlds Republic through the Star League era. Fourteen single heat sinks manage the significant heat output of the particle cannon, though MechWarriors learned to carefully manage their firing cadence during extended engagements.</p>

history:<p>The Phoenix's development began in the late 2460s when several Rim Worlds Republic companies attempted to produce original BattleMech designs. Krauss Heavy Industries, later known as Krauss-Liemann Incorporated, was the only firm to succeed, though the road to production proved tortuous. When AsRoc, the Republic's intelligence agency, acquired jump jet technology samples around 2470, First Consul Terens Amaris ordered the nearly-complete Phoenix prototype to be redesigned for jump capability, a decision that ultimately delayed the project by years.</p><p>The primitive PX-1R prototype first became operational in 2474, but its 240-rated Primitive engine, prototype jump jets, and primitive armor systems resulted in a 'Mech that was noticeably slower and far less reliable than intended. Electronics interference from the particle cannon, combined with structural weaknesses in the legs that could not handle the stresses of a fifty-ton machine landing after jumps, plagued the design through extensive testing. The Republic went so far as to legislate a ban on jump-capable 'Mechs operating within twelve kilometers of any settlement exceeding one thousand people after a Phoenix crashed into a hospital during a training exercise. After nearly a dozen refits, overhauls, and upgrades, these problems were finally corrected by approximately 2490, and the modernized PX-3R entered full production around 2520.</p><p>The Phoenix saw exclusive service with the Rim Worlds Republic's military throughout the Star League era. The design pioneered combat drops from DropShips and the development of urban combat tactics using jump-capable 'Mechs. Phoenix formations became adept at rotating damaged machines through firing positions, forcing opponents to distribute their fire across multiple targets before any single 'Mech suffered critical damage. The Phoenix was extremely capable at running down lighter 'Mechs employed by the Lyran Commonwealth, Draconis Combine, and pirates, and proved moderately successful against heavier units, as it could retreat before sustaining critical damage. Despite these tactical innovations, the Phoenix was never produced in sufficient numbers to offset its limitations against more advanced Inner Sphere designs that increasingly outclassed it.</p><p>Following Aleksandr Kerensky's conquest of the Rim Worlds Republic during the Amaris Civil War, the Phoenix was believed to have been rendered extinct. Production on Wotan and Apollo ceased, and no other state was known to have produced or salvaged the design. ComStar intelligence reports later indicated that the Hanseatic League in the Deep Periphery was deploying several Phoenix 'Mechs, though the source of these machines remains unknown.</p><p>The Phoenix received an unexpected second life during the Jihad when the Kaumberg Archonette in the Lyran Commonwealth ordered the local firm Wechsel Royal Industrial Repair and Heavy Machining (previously a LoggerMech repair facility) to begin manufacturing retrotech Phoenix variants in 3074. This initial production run lasted until 3079, but following the communications collapse of Gray Monday, the facility restarted production with four new variant configurations adapted for the technological realities of the Dark Age. These Kaumberg-built Phoenix 'Mechs continue in production into the ilClan era, giving this ancient design an improbable longevity far beyond anything its Rim Worlds creators could have envisioned.</p>

